@stellabelle In the US you can write your mortgage interest payments off to reduce your taxes. disclaimer: Not accounting advice.

@stellabelle Going further from an opposite analogy.

Let's say your house costs 100k.

Yearly inflation is 7%.

Your house will closely appreciate at that rate, so at the end of the year you now have a house worth roughly $107K.

But you only paid 4K in interest which you can write off.
@stellabelle "gone down" in quotes. The number is still 100K you owe, but 100K is now only 93K in purchasing power this year compared to last.
@stellabelle So while you paid out 4K at the EOY, your initial loan balance has essentially gone down because the purchasing power of 100K has decreased 7%.

@stellabelle Yes - let's say you bought your house last year for 100k at a 4% interest rate. You paid 4K in interest at the end of the year. You can write that off. 

But if inflation is 7%, the 100k you owe basically has become less because the purchasing power of 100k has gone down 7%.
